{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0163fVZGZcjxGWnVVYPgrK3t","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The new pods are crashing because the readiness/liveness probes are failing with \"Authentication failed.\" This is very confusing - the probe command uses the admin password from the secret, so why would it fail?\n\nWait - the new pods (mongodb-replica-3 and mongodb-replica-4) have EMPTY data directories (new PVCs were created). Since these are brand new MongoDB instances, they start without any data. They haven't joined the replica set yet, so they don't have the admin user created. \n\nThe probe uses `mongosh --quiet \"mongodb://admin-user:${ADMIN_PASSWORD}@localhost:27017/admin\" --eval \"db.adminCommand({ping:1})\"` - but on a fresh MongoDB instance that hasn't been added to the replica set yet, there's no admin user, so authentication fails.\nThen the liveness probe kills the pod after enough failures, causing CrashLoopBackOff. The real issue is that with parallel pod startup, fresh instances with keyfile authentication enabled can't authenticate before joining the replica set - there's no admin user yet. I need to either disable authentication checks in the probes until the pods join the replica set, adjust the probe logic, or add the members to the replica set before the liveness probe terminates them.\n\nLet me check the mongod configuration to see how authentication is set up.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1032,"cache_read_input_tokens":35392,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1032},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"791193b7-ea10-4b57-8875-ce093e222cf8","request_id":"req_