{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019Jx6xp2FAZqPPUCStcNA1u","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The mongod.conf has `authorization: enabled` and `keyFile: /etc/mongo-keyfile/keyfile`. \n\nThe key insight: When a new MongoDB member starts with a replica set name configured but NO DATA, it starts as a standalone node with keyfile authentication. The keyfile auth allows internal cluster communication, but the admin user is only in the existing 3-member replica set's data. The new pods (mongodb-replica-3 and mongodb-replica-4) have empty data directories, so they have NO USERS at all. The readiness probe tries to authenticate as `admin-user` but that user doesn't exist yet.\n\nWhat happens when we add a new member with `rs.add()`:\n1. The new member joins the replica set\n2. It starts syncing data from the primary (initial sync)\n3. After the initial sync completes, it will have the admin user in its data\n\nBut the problem is that the liveness probe is killing the pod before it can even be added to the replica set and complete initial sync. Let me check the probe timings more carefully—the readiness probe has 30 seconds before it starts checking, then fails after 60 seconds of repeated failures, while the liveness probe waits 60 seconds before starting and then has its own failure threshold.\n\nSo the readiness probe marks the pod as not ready around 90 seconds (which just affects routing), but the liveness probe would kill it around 210 seconds. Since initial sync can take longer depending on data size, the pod might get terminated before it finishes. The key insight is that we could try adding the new member to the replica set before the liveness probe kills it—once `rs.add()` is called, MongoDB should start receiving data from the primary, which would include the admin user.\n\nBut there's a chicken-and-egg problem: the pod needs to be part of the replica set to get the admin user through initial sync, yet the liveness probe requires admin authentication and will kill the pod before sync completes. I'm considering a few approaches—either temporarily modifying the liveness probe to use keyfile authentication only, or adding members to the replica set and letting them sync while the probe is still running. original probe. MongoDB has a localhost exception that allows unauthenticated access when no users exist, but once users are created, that exception disappears. With keyFile security enabled, internal replica set communication uses the keyfile, but external client connections need the admin credentials—which is what the readiness probe uses.\n\nThe real solution is to temporarily modify the liveness probe to skip authentication or use an anonymous connection, then scale back to the original replica set size.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there's a subtlety here. When a new MongoDB node starts with the replica set name and keyFile configured, it begins as a standalone node that hasn't joined the set yet. At that point, the localhost exception might still apply since there are no users in its local database. Let me think through whether we can connect without authentication in that initial state.\n\nThe real issue is likely that the readiness probe tries to authenticate as admin-user immediately, but the fresh pod has no users at all. So the solution is to add the member to the replica set before the liveness probe times out and kills it. Once it's added, initial sync will replicate the admin user from the primary, and then the probe will pass. Given that the probe starts at 60 seconds and allows about 270 seconds total before failure, we have a narrow window to add the member and let it sync the user credentials.\n\nThe cleanest approach might be to temporarily modify the readiness probe to use a simple ping command that doesn't require authentication, since the keyFile setting enforces authentication even for localhost connections. So the key insight is that unconfigured MongoDB nodes have a localhost exception that allows unauthenticated access, which means I can temporarily modify the liveness probe to skip authentication while the new pods are initializing. Once they join the replica set and complete initial sync, they'll have the admin user created and the probes can switch back to requiring auth.\n\nThe tricky part is that changing the probe command would trigger a rolling restart of all pods through the StatefulSet update, which could destabilize the primary. I need to find a way to update only the new pods without restarting the existing ones.\n\nActually, I can use the `partition` field in the update strategy—setting `partition: 3` means only pods 3 and 4 will get the new spec when I update the StatefulSet, while pods 0, 1, and 2 stay untouched. That's exactly what I need to avoid disrupting the cluster.\n\nSo the approach is: temporarily relax the readiness probe to skip auth checks, update the StatefulSet with `partition: 3`, let pods 3 and 4 restart and stabilize, add them to the replica set via `rs.add()`, wait for the initial sync to replicate the admin user, then restore the strict auth probe and remove the partition to trigger a final rolling update of those pods with the auth check now working.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there's a simpler option—just use a TCP socket probe that only checks if MongoDB is listening on port 27017, bypassing auth entirely. This would work across both the initial bootstrap phase and the normal running state.\n\nSo my approach is to temporarily switch the liveness and readiness probes to TCP socket checks, which lets pods 3 and 4 stay alive during the initial sync. Once they've synced and the admin user exists, I can restore the original exec probes with auth. I'll use the partition strategy to protect the existing pods while rolling out these changes.\n\nWriting the patch command... I'm reconsidering whether a TCP socket probe is actually sufficient for detecting MongoDB health—I really need to verify the database is functional, not just that the port is listening. An exec probe with authentication would be more reliable long-term, but that won't work during initial sync when the admin user doesn't exist yet. Maybe the better approach is to just run the rs.add() command quickly, before the liveness probe has a chance to kill the pod. The pods are already stuck in CrashLoopBackOff, restarting periodically with exponential backoff delays, and each restart gives me a window where mongod starts with an empty data directory before the readiness probe fails and the liveness probe eventually triggers around 270 seconds in. So the readiness and liveness probes are both failing with authentication errors, which means mongod is actually running and responding—it's just rejecting the probe commands. When the liveness probe fails enough times, kubelet kills the container, triggering the CrashLoopBackOff. The timeline shows the container starts, mongod begins, but then the probes fail repeatedly until kubelet terminates it and restarts with exponential backoff.\n\nGiven this, the cleanest approach is to use a tcpSocket probe instead, which bypasses authentication entirely and just checks if the port is listening. The pods are restarting every 5 minutes now due to backoff limits, so I have a reliable window to work with. My best approach is to patch the StatefulSet with a tcpSocket probe for pods 3 and 4 using a partition, which will trigger a rolling update for those pods. Then I can call rs.add() while they're running with the new probe, wait for initial sync to complete, and restore the original probe configuration.\n\nFor the probe itself, I'm weighing tcpSocket (which just checks if the port is open) against an exec probe that runs a ping command. The exec approach is more thorough but might fail if authentication is required, so I need to understand how MongoDB's keyFile authentication works—specifically whether it enforces auth for external clients when no users are configured yet.\n\nThere's a localhost exception in MongoDB: when auth is enabled but the admin database is empty, connections from localhost bypass authentication. Since the new pods have empty data directories, they should allow unauthenticated connections. So I can use a probe that connects without credentials, which would work for both the new empty pods and any existing authenticated instances.\n\nBut once the initial sync completes and an admin user is created, that exception disappears and auth becomes required again. I could work around this by using a probe that attempts authentication first, then falls back to unauthenticated connection if that fails—this way it handles both the initial empty state and the post-sync authenticated state. I'm realizing this approach has a tradeoff: the probe will pass whenever MongoDB is listening, even if authentication fails, which weakens security checks. But for the scaling scenario, it's actually useful—the first command with credentials succeeds after the initial sync completes, and the fallback only kicks in when the admin user doesn't exist yet. The probe fails only if MongoDB is truly down. This works well for our immediate need, though it's not ideal as a permanent solution since it bypasses auth validation.\n\nNow I'm thinking there might be a simpler path: if the replica set has minimal data, the initial sync could complete in under 30 seconds, leaving us 165 seconds before the liveness probe timeout. I could delete pods 3 and 4 to force a restart, quickly add them as members before the probe kills them, and let the sync finish while the probe is temporarily relaxed. the probes start passing once the admin user exists. So the key question is whether initial sync completes within 150 seconds of the liveness probe starting at 60s—that gives a 210-second window total before the pod gets killed. Even though the pods are already in CrashLoopBackOff and will restart, they'll get that same 210-second window each time, but the exponential backoff timer adds another layer of complexity.\n\nIf I use the partition approach and update the pod spec, Kubernetes will delete and recreate pods 3 and 4, which resets their CrashLoopBackOff state entirely—they'll start fresh with the new probe configuration. When I restore the original probe spec and set partition=0, only pods 3 and 4 will actually need updating since pods 0, 1, and 2 already match the desired spec. Now I'll write the JSON patch to update the StatefulSet.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":950,"cache_read_input_tokens":36424,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":950},"output_tokens":46,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"b797865c-271f-46fe-b141-87fa92318790","request_id":"req_011CcP3kPAyJGtzg2N9TGLcp"}
