{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QfAFx3NpnzvszLAcrEXCfz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The error is:\n```\n\"s\":\"F\",  \"c\":\"COMMAND\",  \"id\":40652,   \"ctx\":\"initandlisten\",\"msg\":\"Unable to start up mongod due to missing featureCompatibilityVersion document. Please run with --repair to restore the document.\"\n```\n\nThis is a DIFFERENT problem! The pods have SOME data in their data directory from previous failed runs (from when they were in CrashLoopBackOff with the old probe). The PVCs were retained (`whenScaled: Retain`), but they contain partial/corrupt data from previous attempts.\n\nThe PVCs contain data from when the pods were first created (before we deleted and recreated them). The data is corrupt/partial because:\nThe PVC has actual MongoDB collections with real data (I can see WiredTiger collection tables with records and data sizes), but the critical `featureCompatibilityVersion` document is missing from the system database, which is preventing MongoDB from starting up.\n\nThis happens when initial sync gets interrupted partway through—the node copies some data but never completes the admin database setup. The solution is to clear the PVCs entirely so MongoDB can initialize fresh. I can either delete the pods and use a temporary pod to wipe the PVC contents, or just delete the PVCs themselves and let the StatefulSet recreate them with clean data directories. If I just delete the pod without removing the PVC, the StatefulSet will recreate it using the same corrupted volume, so I need to delete both the pod and the PVC together. Once they're gone, the StatefulSet will spin up fresh pods with new empty volumes. Looking at the MongoDB logs, it seems like an initial sync was actually started and partially completed—that's why there's some data in the PVC but not a complete replica set state.\n\nThe issue is that the initial sync got interrupted before the admin.system.version collection was fully copied, leaving MongoDB in a broken state it can't recover from. My plan is to delete those corrupt PVCs, let the pods restart with clean data directories, and then properly add them back to the replica set through rs.add() so the initial sync can complete correctly this time.\n\nOne more thing to consider: once the initial sync finishes and the data is there, I'll restore the original auth probe by setting partition back to 0. This will trigger a rolling restart of those pods, but since they'll have valid data from the sync, they should start up fine and the auth probe will pass.\n\nNow I'm ready to delete the corrupt PVCs.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4242,"cache_read_input_tokens":48850,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4242},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"4166b30a-fea8-48b4-ae25-a868248c462f","request_id":"req_011CcP4VV58SKgVTqWJYkVEV"}
