{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019oC2Pkj2MFskeBKEsjEYfC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The error is clear:\n```\n\"Authentication failed\", \"principalName\":\"__system\",\"authenticationDatabase\":\"local\",\"error\":\"AuthenticationFailed: SCRAM authentication failed, storedKey mismatch\"\n```\n\nThe primary (mongodb-replica-0, IP 10.244.0.230) is trying to authenticate to the new member (mongodb-replica-3) using SCRAM-SHA-256 with the `__system` user. But this is failing with \"storedKey mismatch\".\n\nThis is a KEYFILE issue. The `__system` user for replica set internal authentication is stored using SCRAM with credentials derived from the keyfile. \n\nWhen MongoDB starts with a keyfile, it generates the `__system` user credentials from the keyfile content using SCRAM-SHA-256. The storedKey mismatch suggests the primary and the new member have different `__system` credentials even though they should be using the same keyfile—which means either the keyfile content differs between them or there's something wrong with how the credentials were derived. same on all nodes, they should all derive the same `__system` credentials. But in the first attempt, pods 3 and 4 got some data through an incomplete initial sync before we deleted those corrupt PVCs. Now with fresh empty data directories, they're being added to the replica set, and the primary should authenticate using the keyfile—yet there's still a mismatch. I think the issue is how MongoDB's keyfile-based SCRAM works: the `__system` user credentials are derived from the keyfile content and then stored in the `local` database, so there might be a disconnect between what's being derived at startup versus what's stored.\n\nWhen a new empty member joins, it has no `__system` user in its `local` database yet, so the primary can't authenticate to it to begin initial sync—but initial sync is what creates that user in the first place. This seems like a chicken-and-egg problem, though MongoDB must have a way to handle this normally. Looking at the docs more carefully, keyfile authentication uses the keyfile content itself as the SCRAM password for the `__system@local` user, not a stored credential.\n\nThe error logs show the authentication is failing with a storedKey mismatch during the `__system` user's SCRAM exchange, which suggests the new member either doesn't have the user initialized yet or has a different keyfile content than the primary.\n\nI'm wondering if the issue is that when I deleted and recreated the PVCs for pods 3 and 4, the StatefulSet might have reused the old PVC names instead of creating fresh ones, leaving behind corrupted local database data with mismatched credentials.\n\nThe key question is whether the underlying PVs were actually cleaned up or retained—if the StorageClass has `reclaimPolicy: Retain`, the old PV data could still be there even after the PVC was deleted, which would explain why the new pod is seeing stale SCRAM credentials.\n\nLet me look at the startup logs to see if MongoDB loaded an existing database or initialized fresh.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3332,"cache_read_input_tokens":62085,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3332},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"22662451-fee2-4779-a68e-e8f7977fcbe2","request_id":"req_011CcP5Eg1eAi5aH12omu4Rq"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019oC2Pkj2MFskeBKEsjEYfC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The keyfile SCRAM authentication is failing — the new pods have an empty `local` database, so `__system@local` credentials don't match yet. This is the bootstrap problem: the primary can't authenticate to add new members because they have no local users yet.\n\nLet me check the secret and keyfile setup, and what the MongoDB docs say about this flow."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3332,"cache_read_input_tokens":62085,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3332},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"7320a95d-c1c4-4f5b-bc3e-526aa7bcba54","request_id":"req_011CcP5Eg1eAi5aH12omu4Rq"}
