{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01P5McMmQxm4uzniPTFrR8pd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so the SCRAM `storedKey mismatch` for `__system@local` is the issue. This means the new members have different SCRAM credentials for `__system` than the existing members.\n\nThis is very puzzling. All members use the same keyfile (from the `mongo-keyfile` secret). The `__system` user credentials are derived from the keyfile in MongoDB's keyfile authentication mode.\n\nLet me think about WHY there would be a mismatch:\n\nIn MongoDB, the keyfile is used for SCRAM-SHA-1 authentication (NOT SCRAM-SHA-256) for the `__system` user. \n\nWhen a new member joins the replica set, it starts with an empty data directory but has the keyfile mounted. The `__system@local` user needs to be initialized, and with MongoDB 6.0, keyfile auth now uses SCRAM-SHA-256 by default. The credentials are stored in the `local` database, but I'm wondering whether MongoDB auto-initializes the `__system` user the same way on new members as it does during initial cluster setup.\n\nLooking at how MongoDB handles this: when a node starts with `--keyFile`, it should create or update the `__system@local` user in the `local` database, deriving the stored key from the keyfile contents. If all nodes use the same keyfile, they should derive the same stored key. But that's not what's happening here—the new node has a completely empty `local` database, so even `local.system.users` doesn't exist yet. The \"storedKey mismatch\" error suggests the user exists but the credentials don't match, which points to a mismatch in how the key was derived or initialized.\n\nActually, thinking about MongoDB's SCRAM implementation more carefully: when a user doesn't exist, the server returns a challenge with a dummy salted password to prevent user enumeration, then the client computes the proof with the actual password. When the server compares the proof against its stored key, if there's no stored key because the user doesn't exist, that would also show as a \"storedKey mismatch.\" So this error could mean the `__system@local` user hasn't been initialized in the new member's empty `local` database yet.\n\nThe core issue is that with `keyFile` authentication always enabled in mongod.conf, I can't temporarily disable auth to perform the initial sync like MongoDB normally does when adding a new member. I need to figure out how MongoDB handles initializing the `__system@local` user on new members before the primary attempts authentication. I can leverage the localhost exception to connect without authentication since the new pods have empty admin databases. Let me check if the `__system` user exists in the local database by running a query directly from within the pod.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4272,"cache_read_input_tokens":67464,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4272},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"b7f7850d-57d0-4e0f-acc9-ce0f62b64354","request_id":"req_011CcP5HusQsvHvH26W3SwUz"}
