e in the command and omit the `security.authorization` setting from the config. Instead of using the config file, I could change the command to start mongod with just the replica set name, data path, and bind address—no authentication layer at all. Once the initial sync completes, I'd update the StatefulSet back to use the full config file with auth enabled, and those pods would restart with the proper credentials.\n\nActually, there's another angle here: the new members already have a `local` database with the `__system` user auto-created, which blocks the localhost exception. But the `admin` database might not have any users yet since these are fresh pods. If I can connect to the admin database without authentication and then modify the `local.system.users` collection directly, that could work. Let me explore whether I can access the admin database and update the user credentials that way. The only viable approaches are starting the new pods without auth so the primary can add them to the replica set, or directly manipulating the persistent volume to remove the local database files—though that would also wipe the replica set configuration that MongoDB needs to function. pods 3 and 4 need to rejoin the replica set after initial sync completes, so I'll need to handle the rs.add() call carefully—potentially using a one-time init container or manual intervention to ensure they're added with the correct replica set configuration before restarting with keyFile auth enabled. The alternative would be to pre-seed the new member's data directory with the `local.system.users` collection from an existing member before it starts with auth enabled. This would require an init container that temporarily starts mongod without auth, imports the credentials, then shuts down so the actual mongod can start with keyFile auth. But that's complex, so let me test the simpler approach first: starting new pods without auth and relying on the primary to connect and sync. The primary should be able to authenticate with its keyFile credentials even if the new member has auth disabled, since a server without auth accepts any connection.\n\nTo verify this works, I'll temporarily override the pod 3 startup command to run mongod with just the replica set name, data path, and bind-all settings—no keyFile authentication—so I can see if the primary can actually reach it and begin the initial sync. Actually, I need to reconsider whether the `local` database gets synced during initial sync. MongoDB doesn't copy the `local` database directly since it's node-specific, but the `__system` credentials might be handled differently—they could be derived from the keyFile instead of synced from the primary.\n\nIf each member generates its `__system` user independently from the keyFile using SCRAM with random salts, that would explain why new members have different stored credentials than existing ones, which seems like a fundamental incompatibility problem. But MongoDB's keyFile authentication clearly works in practice, so I'm missing something about how this actually functions. This would break the whole system since each member would have different stored keys and couldn't authenticate to each other. MongoDB must be handling this differently—either the primary generates the `__system` credentials once during initialization and broadcasts them to all members, or it uses a deterministic approach where the keyFile content serves as both password and salt so all members derive identical credentials. Looking at how MongoDB actually implements keyfile auth, the credentials are generated with random salts but then synchronized across the cluster.\n\nThe real issue is that new members start with their own freshly-generated credentials (different random salt), creating a chicken-and-egg problem where they can't sync because the primary can't authenticate to them. The solution MongoDB recommends is to start new members without auth enabled initially, add them to the replica set, 