{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NwDL5wAmEWGMcEsRL7Fxg3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `__system` user is NOT in either `admin.system.users` or `local.system.users` on the primary! So where are the replica set authentication credentials stored?\n\nWait, maybe the keyFile authentication in MongoDB doesn't use `system.users` at all. Maybe it's handled at a lower level - by directly comparing the keyFile contents as a shared secret, without storing anything in the database.\n\nLet me re-read the MongoDB keyFile auth mechanism. In MongoDB, keyFile authentication is a form of \"internal authentication\" where:\n- The keyFile contains a shared secret that all replica set members use for mutual authentication\n- It's a challenge-response protocol where each member verifies the other knows the secret\n\nSo when Member A connects to Member B, Member B sends a SCRAM challenge, and Member A computes a proof using the keyFile content as the password. Member B then verifies this proof. But here's the thing - in SCRAM, the verifier doesn't actually need the plaintext password to verify the proof. It can use stored credentials like a StoredKey that's derived from the password. So if `__system` isn't in `local.system.users`, how is the verification actually happening?\n\nLooking at the error logs, I see SCRAM authentication is definitely being used - there's a \"storedKey mismatch\" error. But the credentials aren't in `local.system.users` on the primary. Maybe MongoDB treats `__system@local` as a special internal user that isn't stored in that collection. The credentials might be generated on-the-fly from the keyFile content each time, kept in memory rather than persisted. If that's true, then the primary would derive the challenge from the keyFile, but a fresh replica member with a different random state would have different in-memory credentials, which would explain the mismatch. But that still doesn't account for why existing members work fine.\n\nWait - maybe the existing members also don't have `__system` stored in `local.system.users`, but they generate it consistently because they've been running as part of the replica set. The credentials might be stored somewhere else entirely. Let me check if there's another collection like `local.system.keys` that holds the auth keys.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":439,"cache_read_input_tokens":84163,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":439},"output_tokens":41,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"802d7388-2c3a-4445-b175-c983a6f5641d","request_id":"req_011CcP5bgr5xb15Ww1HRun6Q"}
