{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01R7s4WNnVUr6rTHgQ4GQwno","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The new PVC uses a NEW path on the host (`/var/local-path-provisioner/pvc-86cc9583-8b24-44a5-ba88-fad93fdb1c72_mongodb_data-volume-mongodb-replica-3`). This is a different path from the old PVC.\n\nBUT the new PVC was created WHEN? After the old PVCs were deleted. Wait, I scaled down to 3 replicas to allow PVC termination, then scaled back up to 5. The new PVCs were created during the scale-up. They should be using fresh directories.\nBut if the PV is brand new, where are the existing WiredTiger data files in `/data/db` coming from? Let me think through the timing here—when I scaled down to 3 and back up to 5, the pods that were terminated should have released their PVCs, but maybe the deletion didn't complete properly and the pods are still attached to the old corrupted volumes with partial initial sync data.\n\nActually, I'm noticing something in the file identifiers—the WiredTiger storage engine uses a unique identifier that changes with each fresh initialization. The fact that all these files share the same identifier means this data directory wasn't freshly created by this MongoDB instance. It's leftover from a previous failed attempt, which means the data persisted even though we supposedly deleted the PVCs and created new ones.\n\nThe question is how that's possible. When a PVC gets deleted with the local-path provisioner and reclaimPolicy set to Delete, the directory on the host should be cleaned up too. But maybe there's a timing issue where the cleanup didn't happen, or the new PVC ended up pointing to a path that already contained old data from a previous attempt.\n\nActually, wait—the path includes the new PVC's UUID, so it should be completely different from the old one. The new PVC should have a fresh, empty directory. Unless MongoDB itself created those files during startup after we scaled back up. If MongoDB started on a clean data directory, it would initialize its own files, and maybe it's been trying to recover or rebuild something since then.\n\nBut that doesn't explain the \"missing featureCompatibilityVersion document\" error we saw earlier. That was from the previous pods before we deleted the corrupt PVCs. The current pods with fresh PVCs might be in a different state now.\n\nLet me check the current pod's logs to see what's actually happening with the FCV.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":464,"cache_read_input_tokens":86773,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":464},"output_tokens":43,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"eaf1053f-c796-4f62-b6cf-df1b5bf887d0","request_id":"req_011CcP5erJw18RNS5yDPP2qV"}
