{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WCqt98sHtGPmP6LswUwVXE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the pod started at 01:05:57 and the earliest logs show WiredTiger journal flusher. The data directory already has files from startup - this is normal MongoDB initialization.\n\nLet me focus on the real issue: the `__system@local` credentials mismatch.\n\nKey findings:\n1. The PRIMARY does NOT have `__system@local` in `local.system.users` (the collection doesn't even exist in `local` on the primary)\n2. The new members fail with \"SCRAM authentication failed, storedKey mismatch\" for `__system@local`\n3. But the new members DO have `local.system.users` with `__system` stored - just with the wrong credentials\n\nSo there's an asymmetry here: the primary has no stored credentials for `__system`, while the new members have them but they're incorrect. This happens because when MongoDB starts with a keyFile on a fresh data directory, it creates `local.system.users` with `__system` credentials derived from the keyFile. But on existing replica set members, the `__system` user might be managed through a different internal mechanism rather than stored in `local.system.users`.\n\nActually, I think the real explanation is that the existing members (0, 1, 2) generate `__system` credentials dynamically from the keyFile content in memory each time they start - the SCRAM stored key lives in memory, not persisted to disk. The new members (3, 4) do the same thing when they start with the keyFile, but they're generating those in-memory credentials with different random salts, which is why they end up with mismatched credentials when they try to authenticate.\n\nBut this creates a logical problem: if the existing members also generate new random salts on every restart, they should fail to authenticate to each other too. The fact that they don't suggests their `__system` credentials are actually persisted somewhere - either in `local.system.users` on disk (which I'm not seeing) or in the WiredTiger catalog - while the new members are creating their own separate persisted credentials.\n\nLet me dig deeper into the admin credentials by checking if `local.system.users` exists at a lower level that mongosh isn't exposing, and I'll also try running the `usersInfo` command to get more details about the stored user data.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":924,"cache_read_input_tokens":89217,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":924},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"fd33315d-df77-4f82-842d-8bde08d27fb8","request_id":"req_011CcP5h4D7D99Gi46njC38G"}
