{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EnNE5yQSst9KxuvaPY7DQH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`local.system.users` IS empty on the primary! There is NO `__system` user stored there.\n\nYet, the existing members (0, 1, 2) CAN authenticate to each other. But the primary can't authenticate to the new members (3, 4).\n\nThis is very interesting. Let me now check what the new member (3) has in `local.system.users`. The new member requires auth for the `local` database, so I can't connect without credentials. BUT maybe I can query from within the pod using localhost.\n\nActually wait - I thought the localhost exception doesn't apply because local.system.users has `__system`. \n\nBut what if the new members also have an empty `local.system.users`? That would explain the \"storedKey mismatch\" error - MongoDB might be returning that as a generic authentication failure when the user doesn't actually exist, rather than revealing that the user wasn't found (to prevent user enumeration). So the server generates a fake challenge, the client sends a proof based on the keyFile password, and the server can't verify because there's no stored credential to check against.\n\nThis raises a bigger question though: if `local.system.users` is empty on all nodes including the primary, how are the existing members even authenticating to each other? The keyFile authentication must be using a different mechanism than SCRAM credentials stored in that collection. Let me think about what's actually different between the working members and the new ones - the existing members have the replica set configuration and oplog, but what else distinguishes them?","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":623,"cache_read_input_tokens":91389,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":623},"output_tokens":29