{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ULNrknvp7Pv8FTSsFtTqEZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so on the NEW member (replica-3):\n1. The localhost exception is NOT active for the local database\n2. This means there ARE users in the local database (otherwise, the localhost exception would apply to ALL databases)\n3. Specifically, `local.system.users` has the `__system` user with wrong credentials\n\nOn the EXISTING member (replica-1):\n1. The `local` database has NO `system.users` collection\n2. But somehow it can still authenticate to other existing members\n\nHmm wait - I could connect to replica-3 WITHOUT AUTH for the ADMIN database (that's what the mongosh command was doing - connecting to default without auth). \n\nBut accessing the LOCAL database failed with an authorization error. So the ADMIN database on replica-3 has the localhost exception active (no admin users), while the LOCAL database is locked because it has users in `local.system.users`. The problem is that `local.system.users` doesn't exist on replica-1 at all. I think what's happening is that when MongoDB starts fresh with a keyFile, it creates `__system@local` with random SCRAM credentials in `local.system.users`, but when it starts on an existing replica set member, it doesn't create this.\n\nThe existing members have an empty `local.system.users` because they're using a different authentication mechanism now—probably shared cluster auth tokens via `admin.system.keys`. When new members start fresh with keyFile, MongoDB creates that `__system@local` user, but the existing members try to authenticate using their internal cluster key mechanism, which doesn't match the new member's stored SCRAM credentials. When the new member joins the replica set through initial sync, the `__system@local` user gets deleted or the collection is cleared.\n\nSo the catch-22 is that new members can't complete initial sync because authentication fails, and authentication fails because they haven't synced yet. My hypothesis is that if I manually delete the `__system` user from `local.system.users` on the new members, the localhost exception would apply to the admin database, allowing the primary to connect without auth and proceed with initial sync. After sync completes, authentication would work normally. To do this, I'd need to connect to the admin database on the new member without authentication using the localhost exception.\n\nI'm exploring a few approaches: using `db.adminCommand()` for system-level operations, trying `db.getSiblingDB('local').auth()` to bypass restrictions, starting mongod with `--setParameter skipAuthenticationCheck=true`, or even directly manipulating the WiredTiger data files on the Kubernetes node to remove the `local.system.users` collection. I'm leaning toward finding an elegant solution using a specific parameter or command.\n\nActually, I just realized there's a workaround: I can temporarily stop the mongod process in the pod, start a new mongod instance without authentication using the same data directory, delete the `__system` user from `local.system.users`, then shut down the temporary instance and restart mongod with auth enabled through the normal pod restart process.\n\nBut that won't work either because stopping mongod would trigger the liveness probe and restart the container. What if I use `kubectl exec` to spin up a second mongod on a different port within the same pod, using the same data directory but without auth? The problem is WiredTiger uses file locking on the data directory, so two mongod processes can't access it simultaneously. Even running a separate Kubernetes Job that mounts the same PVC would hit the same locking issue—WiredTiger prevents concurrent access to the same data directory regardless of how the processes are started.\n\nThe cleanest approach might be to temporarily patch the StatefulSet to remove the keyFile requirement from the mongod command, then delete pods 3 and 4 so they restart without authentication. This way they'd never create the `__system@local` user in the first place. But then I need to think through what happens when the primary—which still has the keyFile and expects `__system@local` to exist—tries to authenticate against these newly restarted members that have no `__system` user at all.\n\nActually, I think I've got it: when a MongoDB instance runs without authentication enabled, it accepts all incoming connections without validating credentials. So even though the primary sends a SCRAM-SHA-256 challenge for `__system@local`, the new member (running without auth) would just accept the connection without checking whether that user actually exists. This would let the initial sync proceed despite the mismatch.\n\nThe real question is what happens when we restart those new members with keyFile authentication enabled. If MongoDB automatically recreates `__system@local` with random credentials on startup, we'd be stuck in the same authentication loop. But if the node already has the shared cluster keys from `admin.system.keys` after the initial sync, maybe MongoDB uses those for authentication instead of generating new `__system` credentials. That's where the storedKey mismatch error is actually coming from—the primary is trying to authenticate to the new member using credentials that don't match what's stored there. So the keyFile-based authentication is what's happening here. The primary doesn't have `__system@local` stored locally, but it uses the keyFile content as the password to generate a SCRAM proof. The new member does have `__system@local` in its `local.system.users`, but with randomly-generated SCRAM credentials derived from the keyFile—and because the salt is different, the stored key doesn't match what the primary computed, causing verification to fail. The existing members work because they also lack `__system@local` in their user collections, so they're operating under the same keyFile-based mechanism.\n\nI think MongoDB is actually using two separate authentication paths: one for keyFile-based SCRAM (where credentials are derived deterministically from the keyFile content and kept in-memory) and another for traditional SCRAM (where user credentials are stored in `local.system.users` or `admin.system.users`). When a new member starts with the keyFile, it should also derive the same SCRAM credentials deterministically from that keyFile content.\n\nThe problem might be that the new member is creating a `__system@local` entry in `local.system.users` with randomly-generated credentials, which then overrides the in-memory deterministic check when the primary tries to authenticate. If that's the case, deleting the `__system@local` entry from the new member's `local.system.users` would force MongoDB to fall back to the in-memory deterministic credentials derived from the keyFile, which should match what the primary is using.\n\nTo test this, I need to access the new members and delete that entry, but the localhost exception doesn't apply to the `local` database since `__system@local` already exists there. My approach is to start mongod without authentication on the same data directory so I can directly manipulate the database, which means stopping the current mongod first and then restarting it in a repair/setup mode.\n\nThe simplest solution is to start mongod without auth entirely—this bypasses the authentication check even if `__system@local` exists in `local.system.users`. During this no-auth window, I can manually delete that entry from the collection, then restart with keyFile authentication enabled.\n\nThe key question is whether `local.system.users` gets overwritten during initial sync. Since the local database is typically excluded from replication, the entry should persist, which means I need to delete it before restarting with auth to avoid the credential mismatch problem.\n\nBut if I delete `local.system.users` and restart with keyFile, the system will regenerate `__system@local` with random credentials again—unless the keyFile derivation is deterministic, meaning the same keyFile always produces identical SCRAM credentials across all instances.\n\nLet me just test this directly: delete the collection during the no-auth window, restart with keyFile, and see if the new credentials match the existing members. I'm overthinking this—I'll execute the plan and observe what happens. I'll modify the StatefulSet to start pods 3 and 4 without auth, clear their existing data by scaling down, then restart with keyFile enabled. One complication: after restarting with keyFile, does MongoDB use `admin.system.keys` for intra-cluster auth instead of the newly created `local.system.users.__system`? The key insight is that `admin.system.keys` stores the HMAC secrets used for keyFile-based authentication in replica sets, and since the admin database gets synced during initial sync, once a node has those keys, it uses them for internal auth rather than relying on the local SCRAM credentials.\n\nSo when the primary (which has no `__system@local` stored) tries to authenticate using the keyFile, it computes a SCRAM proof based on the keyFile content as the password. But the new member's `local.system.users.__system` has different salt and iteration values, causing a mismatch. The real question is how the primary generates its SCRAM proof when it doesn't have the same user credentials stored—in SCRAM, the server generates the challenge including the salt, so there's a fundamental incompatibility here. with the same salt and iteration count, the stored key should match. So either the server's stored credentials are different, or there's a mismatch in how the salt/iteration is being communicated or applied during the SCRAM exchange. the client, who uses that salt to compute the correct proof).\n\nUnless \"storedKey mismatch\" in MongoDB's implementation means something different. In SCRAM, the server stores the hashed client key and server key, then sends the salt and iteration count during authentication so the client can derive the correct proof. For verification to fail with a storedKey mismatch, the password used to create `__system@local` on the new member must differ from the keyFile content, but I'm trying to figure out when MongoDB would have used a different password to create that user.\n\nThe keyFile comes from a Kubernetes secret that hasn't changed, yet there was an incident where pods had corrupt data from a previous failed sync. When we deleted those PVCs and created fresh ones, the pods reinitialized—but I should verify whether the data directory is truly clean or contains leftover artifacts. The WiredTiger ident in the current pods is a fresh identifier generated on initialization, which suggests the data is from a clean start, not from previous attempts.\n\nWhen MongoDB initializes a fresh data directory with a keyFile, it generates a new WiredTiger identifier, creates the `__system@local` user with the keyFile content as the password, and derives a random salt for SCRAM-SHA-256. The new member's salt is different from the existing members' salts, but that shouldn't matter during authentication—the primary uses the keyFile content plus whatever salt the new member sends in its SCRAM challenge.\n\nThe real issue might be how MongoDB processes the keyFile content itself. It reads the file, trims whitespace, and uses that as the password—so if there's a trailing newline or inconsistent whitespace handling between members, the keyFile content could be interpreted differently, causing the authentication to fail. I need to check what the actual keyFile content is to see if there's a preprocessing issue.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1520,"cache_read_input_tokens":93556,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1520},"output_token