eared, the keyFile derivation should work deterministically on restart. `__system@local` won't work because the primary's SCRAM credentials don't match the new member's. I'm reconsidering whether removing `__system@local` from the new member while bypassing auth could help, or if changing the authentication mechanisms to exclude SCRAM might be the solution. But I'm realizing MongoDB 6.0 fundamentally changed how replica sets authenticate internally compared to earlier versions.\n\nIn MongoDB 6.0, the keyFile generates `__system` credentials using SCRAM-SHA-256 in `local.system.users` for intra-cluster communication, while `admin.system.keys` handles logical session authentication between clients and servers—not replica set internal auth. This means the existing members must have `__system` credentials somewhere, but I'm wondering if they're stored in a way I can't directly see or if they're being handled differently.\n\nLet me query the `usersInfo` command specifically for the `__system@local` user on the primary to see what's actually there.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":239,"cache_read_input_tokens":101422,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":239},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"56d4f18e-e7dd-45c5-aa64-fc42e2325797","request_id":"req_011CcP5x46ppDnYfMqJWYPQa"}
