an restart it with the keyFile and test whether authentication actually works. This should reveal whether the credentials are being synced during the initial replication or if there's some other mechanism at play.\n\nActually, I just realized something important about the error message. The primary (replica-0 at 10.244.0.230) is trying to connect to the new member (replica-3), and the authentication failure is happening on replica-3's side when it receives the SCRAM challenge from the primary. The server (replica-3) is failing to authenticate the client (replica-0) because there's a stored key mismatch during the SCRAM verification process.\n\nThis can only happen if replica-3's `__system@local` user was created with a different password than what the primary is using from the keyFile. The most likely explanation is that when the PVCs were deleted and recreated, the local-path provisioner directories on the host weren't actually cleaned up, so replica-3 is still using leftover data from a previous pod instance that had a different keyFile. I'm wondering if there's a version mismatch in how the keyFile credentials are being generated—maybe the new members are hashing the keyFile differently than the original three, causing the primary's authentication attempt to fail against the stored credentials. Let me check the ConfigMap history to see if the original members were initialized with different MongoDB versions or configurations. All pods are running the same MongoDB version, so the credential generation logic should be identical. I'm going to try the simpler approach of running the new pods without auth initially to see if that resolves the issue empirically. My plan is to patch the StatefulSet to disable auth for pods 3 and 4, delete their PVCs to start with clean data directories, scale down and back up to trigger fresh initialization, add them to the replica set, wait for sync to complete, then re-enable auth and restart them.\n\nNow I'm working on the actual imp