{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Cyb1zgb4f93ERewhMfadLs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"BRILLIANT! Now I can see the exact error:\n\n```\n\"error\":\"AuthenticationFailed: It is not possible to authenticate as the __system user on servers started without a --keyFile parameter\"\n```\n\nThis is KEY: MongoDB explicitly REFUSES `__system` authentication on servers started WITHOUT a keyFile. This is a security feature - a server without keyFile cannot be part of an authenticated replica set.\n\nAlso:\n```\n\"error\":\"BadValue: SCRAM-SHA-256 is disallowed for cluster authentication\"\n```\n\nSo starting without keyFile makes the new member IMPOSSIBLE to authenticate to by the existing members.\nSo the \"start without auth\" approach won't work in MongoDB 6.0. I need to figure out the correct way to add new members to a keyFile-secured replica set. The core problem is that when a new member starts with a fresh data directory and a keyFile, it creates its own `__system@local` user with random SCRAM credentials, but the existing members try to authenticate using the keyFile as the password—which fails because the salt is different. But if I can't start without a keyFile, how does MongoDB normally handle adding new members?\n\nThe answer has to be that when new members start with the same keyFile and fresh data directories, their `__system@local` credentials should be compatible with the existing members. Let me reconsider whether the SCRAM credentials are actually random on each fresh start. In SCRAM authentication, the salt is random and the stored key is derived from that salt, but the server sends its salt to the client during the challenge. The client uses that salt to compute the proof, and the server verifies it against its stored key—which was derived from the same salt. So verification should work as long as both sides use the same salt and password.\n\nA \"storedKey mismatch\" error would only occur if the password differs or if the server's stored key was derived from a different salt than what the client received in the challenge. The server wouldn't send a mismatched salt in the challenge—that would defeat the purpose of the protocol.\n\nSo the mismatch must mean a different password is being used. But the keyFile is identical across all members, which is puzzling. I'm wondering if the password for `__system@local` isn't the raw keyFile content itself, but some transformation of it. And I'm noticing something critical: the existing members (0, 1, 2) don't have `__system@local` in their `local.system.users` collection, while the new members (3, 4) do. The primary authenticates using the keyFile as the password, and if the new members have `__system@local` credentials derived from that same keyFile, the proof should match—unless the existing members are authenticating through a completely different mechanism.\n\nThe existing members might be using JWT tokens from `admin.system.keys` instead of SCRAM authentication with `__system@local`. When the primary tries to connect to the new members with `__system@local` SCRAM, it fails because the new members were initialized with a different password for that user. This could happen if the keyFile was regenerated or changed between when the existing members were created and when the new ones were added. The StatefulSet restart timestamp suggests all pods were restarted at the same time, so I need to trace back whether the keyFile content actually changed during that restart. So the existing members should have an empty `local.system.users` after the initial sync removed `__system`, while the new members still have `__system@local` with credentials derived from the keyFile. When the primary tries to authenticate to a new member using `__system@local` SCRAM with the keyFile as the password, the verification should work since both sides derived the credentials from the same keyFile—but it's failing with a \"storedKey mismatch.\" This suggests the primary might be sending a different SCRAM mechanism than what the new member expects.\n\nLooking at the error messages more carefully: with keyFile enabled I'm getting \"storedKey mismatch,\" but without keyFile the error is \"not possible to authenticate as __system.\" Neither approach works, which means I need to find the correct procedure for adding members to a keyFile-authenticated replica set. Let me check the MongoDB documentation on how member authentication is supposed to work during replica set expansion.\n\nThe standard process should be straightforward—create a new mongod with the same keyFile, then call rs.add()—but the \"storedKey mismatch\" error suggests something's wrong with how the keyFile is being handled. I've already verified the keyFile content is exactly 28 characters with no trailing newline, so now I should check if the file permissions are set correctly on the new pods.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1411,"cache_read_input_tokens":109277,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1411},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"b0f97121-dc77-4340-8903-de3b1cef2ce7","request_id":"req_011CcP6CD6CoGXD8eM5yXoZX"}
