{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DWFfUo7rm8ZKsL716WoPi6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The keyFile has permissions `-r--------` (owner: root, read-only). This is correct for MongoDB keyFile requirements.\n\nOK let me think about this from a completely different angle. Let me check what happens on the EXISTING members when they were FIRST ADDED to the replica set. Looking at the existing setup:\n\nThe StatefulSet was RESTARTED (`restartedAt: \"2026-06-24T19:24:39-05:00\"`). This means all pods (0,1,2) were restarted. But they kept their PVC data.\nBefore the restart, pods 0, 1, 2 had been running as a proper 3-member replica set. After the restart, they resumed with the same keyFile. The restart was a ROLLING RESTART (not a fresh initialization), so the data was preserved.\n\nNow when the new pods (3, 4) are created, they start fresh and generate `__system@local` with the keyFile password but a new random salt. The primary tries to authenticate and fails.\n\nBut here's what I've been missing: the `__system@local` user isn't stored in `local.system.users` the way I thought. When a member starts with a keyFile in MongoDB,\n\nit reads the keyFile and creates an in-memory `__system@local` user whose SCRAM credentials are derived deterministically from the keyFile content—not randomly. This ensures all members with the same keyFile have identical credentials. When I query `local.system.users` and it's empty, that's because the `__system@local` user exists only in memory, not persisted to disk.\n\nSo when a new member starts with the same keyFile, it should derive the same in-memory SCRAM credentials and authentication should succeed. But something is different.\n\nThe new members actually have `local.system.users` populated with `__system@local` stored there—whereas the existing members don't have this collection at all. This is the key difference. I think what's happening is that when a MongoDB node starts fresh with a keyFile on an empty data directory, it initializes `local.system.users.__system` with credentials derived from the keyFile, but the SCRAM salt used during this initialization is random. So the existing members (0, 1, 2) must have had their `local.system.users` collection cleaned up or the `__system@local` entry removed during their initial sync, leaving them with only the in-memory keyFile-derived credentials.\n\nThe new members (3, 4) haven't completed initial sync yet, so they still have that randomly-generated `__system@local` stored in `local.system.users`. When the primary tries to authenticate using its deterministic in-memory credentials, the new members check against their stored randomly-generated credentials—and they don't match.\n\nThe solution would be to delete `__system@local` from `local.system.users` on the new members so they fall back to the in-memory keyFile credentials, which would then match the primary's credentials and allow authentication to succeed. But I'm trying to figure out how to do this without authentication, or whether the primary can connect directly to the new members to perform this operation.\n\nI'm realizing the new members' admin database is empty (no admin users), so the localhost exception should apply—meaning I can connect to the admin database without authentication. If I can do that, I might be able to manipulate `local.system.users` by dropping the problematic entry.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":194,"cache_read_input_tokens":112925,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":194},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"9ef00a40-544e-4140-af65-f7a16a11f13b","request_id":"req_011CcP6FTQG2x