{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015zSwusNqGJjSD7Cj9b1w9p","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"MongoDB REQUIRES the keyFile when authorization is enabled with replica sets. So `--auth` without `--keyFile` in a replica set context doesn't work.\n\nOK. So the combinations we've tried:\n1. `--config /etc/mongo-config/mongod.conf` (keyFile + auth): starts, but primary can't auth (storedKey mismatch)\n2. Without config (no keyFile, no auth): starts, but primary can't auth (\"not possible to authenticate as __system without --keyFile\")\n3. `--auth` (no keyFile): crashes (\"security.keyFile is required when authorization is enabled with replica sets\")\nNone of these approaches work for getting the primary to connect to the new member. The real problem is that the `__system@local` SCRAM credentials on the new pods have a different salt than what the primary expects. I need to think through what actually happens during initial sync—when the original members started with keyFile and rs.initiate() was called, each created their own `__system@local` credentials. But when members 1 and 2 synced from the primary, what happened to their local.system.users collection?\n\nThe local database doesn't replicate normally, so their `__system` credentials should have stayed different from the primary's. Yet somehow they can authenticate to each other. Maybe the oplog replication includes entries that overwrite the `__system` user during initial sync, even though MongoDB claims local changes don't go into the oplog. Let me step back and compare what's actually different between the existing members (0, 1, 2) and the new ones (3, 4)—the existing members have an empty local.system.users collection with no `__system` user, but they can still authenticate.\n\nThe new members have `__system@local` with random credentials and can't authenticate. This suggests that during initial sync, MongoDB might explicitly clear the `__system` user from local.system.users as a security measure, even though the local database itself isn't replicated. If that's true, the solution is getting past initial sync—once it completes, `__system@local` gets removed and subsequent connections fall back to the in-memory keyFile credentials, which are deterministic and match across all members. The challenge is getting past initial sync when the primary can't connect. Looking at the storedKey mismatch error more carefully, I'm reconsidering what it actually means—the SCRAM-SHA-256 flow involves the server looking up `__system@local`, generating a challenge with the stored salt, and the client computing a proof using the keyFile password plus that salt, then the server verifying against the stored key.\n\nThe issue might be that the keyFile content is being processed differently between the server and client—the raw keyFile string versus a base64-decoded version. MongoDB's documentation says keyFile characters outside the base64 set are ignored, but `mongoKeyfile0123456789ABCDEF` is all valid base64 characters, so it should be used as-is. I'm wondering if there's a behavior difference when nodes start standalone versus as part of an existing replica set, and whether calling `rs.initiate()` triggers MongoDB to clear `__system@local` from local.system.users as part of initializing the replica set protocol.\n\nIf that's the case, the new members (3, 4) still have `__system@local` stored with incorrect credentials, while the primary has switched to a different internal auth mechanism post-initialization. This would explain why the primary can't authenticate with the new members—they're still checking `__system@local` while the primary isn't using it anymore. The fix would require forcing the new members through initialization to clear that entry, but that creates a catch-22 since I can't connect to them without auth.\n\nLet me try a different angle: I could use WiredTiger tools to directly remove the `__system@local` entry from the disk, or use mongodump/mongorestore to extract and reimport the data without the problematic `local.system.users`. The most drastic option would be clearing the entire `local` database files on the new pods—this removes `__system@local` along with the replica set config and oplog, forcing MongoDB to reinitialize from scratch.\n\nThe challenge is that WiredTiger locks files while mongod is running, so I'd need to stop the process, delete the files, and restart it all within the container before Kubernetes detects the exit and restarts the pod. I could exec into the pod and run a script that kills mongod, deletes the local database files, and immediately restarts mongod—all before the container exits and triggers a restart.\n\nBut this is getting complicated. A cleaner approach would be to use an init container that runs before the main mongod starts, though that has its own problem: two mongod instances can't access the same data directory simultaneously due to WiredTiger's file locking. I could instead have the init container directly modify the WiredTiger data files using a script rather than starting a separate mongod instance.\n\nAlternatively, I could try using `--setParameter` flags like `enableTestCommands=true` or adjusting `authenticationMechanisms` to bypass SCRAM authentication entirely. But the most straightforward solution might be to change the keyFile itself—if I update the keyFile content, all members would need to restart, and when the new members come up with the new keyFile, they'd generate fresh `__system@local` credentials based on it.\n\nThe problem is that existing members store `__system@local` differently than new members do, so even after a rolling restart with the new keyFile, there could still be a credential mismatch. I need to think through whether restarting all members with a changed keyFile would actually synchronize their `__system@local` credentials across the board. If the SCRAM credentials get regenerated when the keyFile changes, then the rolling restart that already happened should have resolved this—but the new pods' `__system@local` was created after that restart, so it would have the current keyFile's credentials. I'm shifting perspective to think about how MongoDB's UserManager initializes: when it starts with a keyFile, it checks if `__system` exists in `local.system.users`, and if the stored credentials don't match what's derived from the keyFile, that's when the storedKey mismatch error occurs during authentication. I'm wondering whether MongoDB regenerates these credentials automatically or if there's a specific condition that triggers it. The keyFile content is identical across all pods based on the md5sum check, so that's not the issue. I'm wondering if I should try copying the actual WiredTiger collection file for `local.system.users` from an existing member directly to the new members to see if that resolves the credential mismatch.\n\nThe approach would be to stop the new members, copy the files from an existing member, then restart with keyFile so MongoDB recreates `__system@local` from the keyFile deterministically. The challenge is handling WiredTiger file locking and coordinating the timing of the copy operation with container restarts, possibly using an init container to copy files before the main mongod process starts. Writing helper pod config...\n\nThe issue is that PVCs with `ReadWriteOnce` can only be mounted by one pod at a time, so I can't mount the same PVC in both the original pod and a helper pod simultaneously. I'd need to scale down the StatefulSet completely, but that would cause the pods to be recreated automatically. A simpler approach might be to use host-level access instead.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the core problem here: when MongoDB initializes with a keyFile, it creates the `__system@local` user with random SCRAM credentials using a specific salt. When the PRIMARY tries to authenticate to new replica members, it uses the keyFile content as the password, but those new members have different stored credentials with a different salt. In SCRAM authentication, the client computes its proof using the password and the salt from the server's stored entry, so there's a mismatch in how the credentials were generated versus how they're being verified.\n\nThis seems like it could be a version-specific bug in MongoDB 6.0.5's SCRAM-SHA-256 implementation for keyFile authentication. Rather than continuing down this path, let me try a different approach: I'll access the PVC data directly through the KIND node's filesystem to manually remove or modify the `__system@local` entry on the new pods before they join the replica set. a degraded state. The replica set metadata might prevent standalone mode from working cleanly. Let me think about whether I can strip the replica set state from the data directory first, or if there's a way to force standalone mode to ignore it. Starting mongod without authentication or keyFile flags should allow me to connect freely, though there's a risk it might fail if the replica set state in the data directory conflicts with standalone mode. I'm planning to access the KIND cluster node directly through kubectl to test this approach on the actual PVC data.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":140,"cache_read_input_tokens":122165,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":140},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"971a44b2-e04e-41f4-924f-3c3dc8d7c5ca","request_id":"req_011CcP6j1r9EV6AHESvTewmn"}
