{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MdSUrwSK5eWSAqjUvhrYoB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The data directories have WiredTiger files. Now I need to start mongod in these directories WITHOUT auth (no keyFile, no --auth) to be able to connect and delete `local.system.users.__system`.\n\nBut the issue: Can I start mongod with `--replSet` on this data that was previously in a replica set? If I start WITHOUT `--replSet`, it might not recognize the data.\n\nActually, let me start mongod in STANDALONE mode (WITHOUT `--replSet`) with NO auth. This should:\n1. Ignore the replica set state\n2. NOT create `__system@local` (no keyFile)\n3. Allow unauthenticated access\n\nThen I can connect without credentials, delete `__system@local` from `local.system.users`, and stop mongod.\n\nWait—starting standalone on a data directory with replica set state could fail or corrupt the data. But MongoDB documentation actually allows starting a replica set member as standalone for maintenance. The `--replSet` flag determines whether it acts as a replica set member, but I can start it without that flag for maintenance operations. When running standalone without `--replSet`, MongoDB will use the existing data as-is.\n\nSo my approach is: exec into the helper pod, start mongod on `/data3` with a different port, no auth, and no replSet flag, then connect and delete `__system@local`. Repeat for `/data4`, delete the helper pod, scale the StatefulSet back to 5, and when the pods restart with the keyFile, they'll regenerate `__system@local` with deterministic credentials that should work.\n\nThe question is whether those regenerated credentials will be deterministic or random again. If they're random, I'm back where I started. But there's a chance that once the initial auth succeeds (since `__system@local` was removed), the primary can connect and sync, potentially clearing the stored credentials on existing members through the oplog—though I know `local` database entries don't replicate normally. I'm going in circles on the theory, so let me just try it empirically.\n\nMy plan: clear `__system@local` from the new pods, restart with the keyFile, and see if authentication works now with fresh SCRAM credentials. If it does, the existing members must be using deterministic credentials from the keyFile. If it still fails, something else is different about them.\n\nBefore I proceed, I need to handle the WiredTiger lock file—the data directory still has a lock from the previous mongod instance that needs to be cleared before a new one can start.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":650,"cache_read_input_tokens":129294,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":650},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"07c4d71f-9352-4f13-a624-7144923f9898","request_id":"req_011CcP6uDzRYqYFaf3SXHzLL"}
