{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01See71tW2tprjs67zrZzJhX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Key insight:\n- `local.system.users`: NOT in the collection list (doesn't even exist!)\n- `admin.system.keys`: has 0 entries\n\nCompare to existing members (0, 1, 2):\n- `local.system.users`: IS in the collection list (but empty)\n- `admin.system.keys`: presumably has entries (they're a functioning replica set)\n\nSo the new members (3, 4) do NOT have:\n1. `local.system.users` (doesn't exist at all)\n2. `admin.system.keys` (exists but empty)\nThe existing members have both collections—`local.system.users` exists but is empty, and `admin.system.keys` contains the JWT keys from replica set initialization. The new members are missing these entirely, which means when the primary tries to authenticate using JWT-based internal authentication, it fails and falls back to SCRAM-SHA-256 instead. they had the keyFile. So when nodes 1 and 2 were added, they could authenticate using the keyFile-based SCRAM credentials until they synced the `admin.system.keys` collection. The new members are stuck because they never had access to the keyFile in the first place—they can't authenticate to do the initial sync that would give them the keys they need. I'm reconsidering how MongoDB's keyFile authentication actually works. Each member reads the keyFile and deterministically generates the in-memory `__system@local` credentials for SCRAM-SHA-256, so when nodes 1 and 2 started with the same keyFile, they should have been able to derive the same credentials. But then when new members join without the keyFile, they can't generate those credentials, and the primary's JWT auth attempt fails because they lack `admin.system.keys`, forcing a fallback to SCRAM that can't succeed. The SCRAM-SHA-256 hash algorithm might be different from what was used when nodes 0, 1, 2 were initialized, or the iteration count changed—either way,