rver then verifies using the same salt it generated. So random salts should actually work fine.\n\nI need to stop theorizing and look at what's actually failing. When pods 3 and 4 ran with a fresh keyFile and fresh data, the logs showed the authentication challenge was sent but then failed with a \"storedKey mismatch\" error from the server side. The data directory doesn't have the `local.system.users` collection at all, which means it should be falling back to in-memory credentials.\n\nIf in-memory credentials exist but don't match, that's the real problem. Let me try a different approach—restore the keyFile config for pods 3 and 4, start them, and immediately check whether authentication is actually failing or if the primary is trying JWT first. Or maybe I should step back entirely and understand what `rs.add()` actually requires in terms of connectivity and configuration.\n\nWhen a new member is added, the primary sends heartbeats using `isMaster` (or `hello` in newer versions), and I'm seeing the primary attempt speculative authentication for `__system@local` right in that heartbeat command. If that speculative auth fails with a storedKey mismatch, the primary closes the connection and can't proceed with initial sync.\n\nI'm wondering what could cause speculative auth to fail even when the credentials should match. The keyFile itself looks valid—`mongoKeyfile0123456789ABCDEF` is 28 characters of alphanumeric content, which fits MongoDB's 6-1024 character requirement for base64 characters. But I'm noticing the keyFile is mounted as a symlink, and there might be encoding differences or symlink resolution issues affecting how MongoDB reads it.\n\nI've already verified the actual bytes with `od -c` and confirmed there's no trailing newline, so the content is exactly what I expect. Now I'm thinking I should examine the WiredTiger catalog files more closely, particularly whether `local.system.users` is properly mapped in the new data directory. I can query the standal