{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LCsCC6xKU2H1XG9FmWKMa3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Even clusterAdmin can't access `admin.system.keys`. This is a special privileged collection that only `__system` user can access.\n\nLet me check it via the standalone mongod on the helper pod, but for the EXISTING member's data. Actually, I can check by starting a standalone mongod on data from a WORKING pod (0, 1, or 2).\n\nBut those pods are RUNNING, so their PVCs are locked. I can't mount them in a helper pod.\n\nUnless I use the KIND node Docker container to access the host filesystem directly.\n\nActually, let me take a completely fresh approach. Let me check what the actual authentication mechanism looks like step by step.\nThe real issue is why SCRAM authentication fails when the keyFile is identical. The storedKey mismatch error means the server can't verify the client's proof. For SCRAM-SHA-256, this involves a chain of cryptographic operations: the server sends salt and iterations in the challenge, the client derives the SaltedPassword using PBKDF2 with the keyFile as the password, then computes the ClientKey and proof, and the server verifies by comparing the computed hash of ClientKey against its stored value.\n\nThe failure could stem from three possibilities: the client using a different password (ruled out since the keyFile md5sum matches), the server's stored credentials being derived from a different password (but local.system.users is empty), or the server's in-memory credentials being generated with a different SCRAM algorithm. That third option is worth exploring—if old cluster members were using SCRAM-SHA-1 while new members switched to SCRAM-SHA-256, there'd be a mismatch. But since all pods run mongo:6.0.5, the algorithm should be consistent across the board.\n\nLooking at the actual SCRAM exchange, the primary sends SCRAM-SHA-256 and the new member rejects with a storedKey mismatch. Since local.system.users is empty on the new member, MongoDB likely uses a fake stored key to prevent user enumeration, and verification against that fake key fails. But if old members also have empty local.system.users, they should hit the same issue—yet they authenticate successfully to each other, suggesting they're not using SCRAM-SHA-256 for `__system@local` at all. Maybe the primary is actually using JWT from admin.system.keys instead.\n\nThe real problem might be that when the primary connects to new members without admin.system.keys, it falls back to SCRAM-SHA-256 using the keyFile-derived password. The new member has no stored credentials to verify against, so it generates a fake challenge and the verification fails. Both sides have empty local.system.users but in-memory keyFile credentials—the authentication should work with those in-memory credentials, yet the new member is returning storedKey mismatch instead of using them.\n\nRather than continuing to debug the authentication mechanism, I'm going to take a different approach: seed the admin.system.keys collection from an existing member into the new members. This way the primary can authenticate using JWT (the primary mechanism) and bypass the SCRAM fallback entirely. I'll stop the standalone mongod on /data3 and copy the keys over.\n\nBut I'm realizing I can't access the existing members' PVCs while they're running, unless I exec into the KIND node directly and work with the filesystem. Let me check what's actually in the admin.system.keys collection on the standalone mongod I already started on port 27030 for /data3 — I found it's empty, so the new member's data directory has no system keys at all. I need to check what the helper member has.\n\nActually, let me try a different approach: using mongodump/mongorestore to copy admin.system.keys from an existing member. The challenge is that admin.system.keys requires special privileges like __system or keyManager, which mongodump might not have access to. I'm wondering if I can authenticate as the __system user directly on an existing member using the keyFile credentials, since that would give me access to all collections including the system keys.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":387,"cache_read_input_tokens":136636,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":387},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"367501ed-e4a5-4000-b239-5419541c94df","uuid":"b9f4f582-58ea-4251-b45f-b8ed1cdb5e43","request_id":"req_011CcP74nKrXykKCUAT93Rcp"}
