{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017KofKqDqCHF5Gpb4dp7PrM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Can't auth as `__system` externally. Let me try a different approach.\n\nActually, let me look at what the KIND node has in its host filesystem. I can exec into the kind-1-control-plane container and directly work with the local-path data directories.\n\nLet me also verify: the `admin.system.keys` on an existing member (replica-0, 1, or 2) - how many keys does it have? I know the current pods have it and the new pods don't. Let me try to get this info through a different means.\nActually, I'm realizing there might be a much simpler solution here. The `admin.system.keys` collection contains the key identifiers and HMAC-SHA-1 key pairs used for internal authentication between replica set members—these are generated when the replica set is initiated. After initial sync, all members should have these keys, but new members that haven't synced yet won't have them.\n\nThe problem is that `admin.system.keys` isn't accessible via the `clusterAdmin` role—it requires the `__system` user role, which I can't use with mongodump. But there has to be a documented way to add new members to an existing secure replica set, so let me check the MongoDB documentation on initial member authentication to see how this is supposed to work.\n\nAccording to the docs, for keyFile authentication it's straightforward: copy the keyFile to the new member and restart with `--keyFile`. That should work automatically, but it's not. The only difference I can identify is the missing `admin.system.keys` collection on the new members.\n\nActually, I just realized the new pods might have leftover WiredTiger files from previous failed attempts in their data directories, which could be causing issues even though I thought I deleted them. log, system.rollback.id, replset.oplogTruncateAfterPoint, replset.election, system.views, replset.minvalid, system.tenantMigration.oplogView` in the local database, plus `system.version` and `system.profile` in admin. The `admin.system.keys` collection is empty, and there's no `local.system.users` or `local.system.replset`, which is odd for a replica set member that should have been initialized. I'm noticing the replica set collections are present but incomplete—I see `replset.election` and `replset.minvalid` but I need to verify whether `system.replset` actually exists in the collection list. The new members have some replica set state from being started with `--replSet`, but they're missing the actual configuration from `local.system.replset`. They need to fetch it from the primary, but that requires authentication—another chicken-and-egg problem. I think the cleanest approach is to wipe all the local data directories completely and start fresh without any lingering replica set history or stale state from previous authentication attempts. The \"storedKey mismatch\" error for `__system@local` when `local.system.users` is empty suggests MongoDB is generating a fake challenge to prevent user enumeration, but then the proof validation fails because the server's stored key doesn't match what the client computed. I'm realizing the issue might be that when pods start fresh with keyFile, they're deriving `__system` in-memory, but the authentication handshake is breaking down because the server-side proof check expects something different than what the keyFile-derived credentials produce. the PRIMARY might try JWT first, which fails on the new members since they lack the admin.system.keys, then falls back to SCRAM. Or maybe MongoDB uses SCRAM directly for `__system@local` when a member hasn't been initialized yet. The real issue could be that while the new member might have `__system@local` in memory, the SCRAM handler checks `local.system.users` first and only falls back to in-memory if it's not found there.\n\nI'm thinking the bug might be in how MongoDB handles the anti-enumeration fake challenge: when `__system` isn't found in `local.system.users`, the server generates a fake challenge to prevent user enumeration, but the actual in-memory keyFile verification might not be implemented or is broken, causing the authentication to fail even though the credentials match. This would explain why existing members can authenticate to each other—they've already gone through `rs.init()` and have the proper setup. The timing might be the issue—when the primary adds a new member and immediately starts heartbeats, the new pod might still be loading its keyFile credentials from disk, creating a race condition where authentication is attempted before the credentials are ready. The heartbeat retries every 2 seconds, so temporary failures should recover, but I'm wondering if there's corrupted data in pods 3 and 4 from previous failed attempts that's preventing a clean restart.\n\nLet me try a different strategy: instead of fighting the authentication issue, I'll seed the `admin.system.keys` collection from an existing member into the new members before enabling keyFile authentication. The approach would be to scale down to just the original three members, delete the PVCs for pods 3 and 4, then use a helper pod to copy the necessary key data into fresh volumes before bringing the new members online.\n\nThe tricky part is accessing `admin.system.keys` from an existing member—I can't query it with the admin user since it's a system collection. I could try running a standalone mongod against one of the existing member's data directories while the replica set is scaled down, but that would cause the primary to step down and lose quorum.\n\nInstead, I'll access the KIND node's host filesystem directly by exec'ing into the control plane container and locating the local-path-provisioner directories where the persistent volumes are stored.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creatio