{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YBGS8cQb1KzZCHduN7UU2m","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"mongod is not available in the kind node container. The kind node is a Kubernetes node, not a container with MongoDB installed.\n\nLet me try a different approach. I can copy the WiredTiger files for admin.system.keys from the existing member's hostPath directory to the new member's hostPath directory.\n\nBUT: this is risky because WiredTiger uses internal consistency checks. Copying individual collection files might cause inconsistencies if the catalog doesn't know about them.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach would be:\n1. Stop the standalone mongod on /data3 (running on port 27030 in the helper pod)\n2. Use mongorestore to import admin.system.keys into /data3 and /data4\n\nBut I can't access the keys from outside. What if I scale down one of the existing secondaries, then create a helper pod that mounts both that secondary's PVC and the new member's PVC? That way I can run a standalone mongod on the secondary's data to export the keys and import them into the new member's data directory. The challenge is that scaling down the StatefulSet would leave only two members, which could be problematic.\n\nActually, let me think through the voting math here. With a 3-member replica set, if I scale to 2 members, I'd have the primary and one secondary still active, which maintains quorum since 2 out of 3 votes is a majority. But scaling the StatefulSet would permanently remove pods in reverse order, and the replica set config would still reference the removed member, potentially causing election issues.\n\nThe better approach is to scale back up to 4 members first, let the new pod start fresh with the keyFile, and then attempt authentication from within that pod using the keyFile credentials to work around the SCRAM authentication issue.\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering the whole strategy. What if I use `