{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01296cuyt2mBdGp2dykGhxMS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Can't dump admin.system.keys with admin-user. Let me think about a different way.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider the entire problem. Maybe I've been approaching this wrong.\n\nLet me re-read the error message CAREFULLY:\n```\n\"mechanism\":\"SCRAM-SHA-256\",\"principalName\":\"__system\",\"authenticationDatabase\":\"local\",\"error\":\"SCRAM authentication failed, storedKey mismatch\"\n```\n\nThis occurs when pods 3,4 are running with keyFile AND fresh data.\n\nAnd from the standalone mongod check, `local.system.users` doesn't exist on the fresh data.\nSo the SCRAM failure is happening because the `__system@local` user doesn't actually exist in the database—the storedKey mismatch is MongoDB's way of hiding that the user wasn't found. The question is whether mongod with keyFile should be auto-creating this user on startup when `security.authorization: enabled` is set. Both are configured in our setup, so MongoDB should be generating the in-memory `__system@local` credentials, but something's preventing that from happening.\n\nI need to figure out what `local.system.users` actually contains when the pod runs with keyFile enabled. Since I can't connect to the pod directly due to the auth failure, I could try starting a standalone mongod on a separate volume WITH keyFile to see if it properly initializes the system user—though that would also require authentication, which complicates checking the contents.\n\nThe key insight is that when the standalone mongod runs without keyFile, `local.system.users` stays empty, but when the full pod runs WITH keyFile, it seems to create `__system@local` in memory rather than persisting it to disk. This in-memory user exists only during that run, which explains why the primary's SCRAM authentication fails—the stored key verification doesn't match because the credentials aren't being properly synchronized.\n\nSo the SCRAM flow becomes: the new member receives a challenge and needs to decide whether to use the fake salt (anti-enumeration) or the real one. The critical question is whether MongoDB falls back to verifying against the keyFile-derived credentials when the user doesn't exist in `local.system.users`. I think it does—when there's no stored user but keyFile is configured, MongoDB uses the keyFile password with the deterministic salt from the challenge, allowing the client to produce the same proof and pass verification.\n\nBut here's the catch: if the server sends a fake salt for anti-enumeration purposes, the client computes the proof using that fake salt, while the server's in-memory key was derived from the real deterministic salt. They won't match. The solution is to ensure `__system@local` actually exists in `local.system.users` with the correct credentials derived from the keyFile, so the server sends the real challenge with the real salt instead of triggering the anti-enumeration fake salt.\n\nThe question is whether MongoDB creates this user automatically during initialization on a fresh data directory. I should test this by starting a standalone mongod with the keyFile mounted and checking if `__system@local` appears in `local.system.users`. I can do this using the helper pod with the same mongo image, though I'll need to mount the keyFile secret first. I'll test with a fresh data directory and keyFile using the mongo:6.0.5 image to see if mongod creates the `__system@local` user when initialized with key file authentication.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1614,"cache_read_input_tokens":143494,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1614},"output_tokens":36,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_